  <chapter id="intro">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <sect1 id="whatis">
      <title>What is ZeroTao</title>
      <para>
	ZeroTao represents a lack of life.  It is basicly my desire to 
	stop wasting time redoing things for each project that I do and 
	collect all of that knowledge into on place.
      </para>
    </sect1>
    <sect1 id="thisdoc">
      
      <title>This Document</title>
      <warning>
	<para>
	  This document is in its early stages.  So it is almost certainly
	  going to contain errors in what data has been inserted.  When this 
	  document and the code disagree, the code wins.
	</para>
      </warning>
      <para>
	This document is intended to be used as a tutorial and reference.  It will guide 
	you thru the use and extention of &lzt; as well as give you a deeper understanding
	the inner workings if that is what you desire.
      </para>
    </sect1>
    
    <sect1 id="conventions">
      <title>Conventions and Typographical Features</title>
      <para>
	Here we will describe some of the conventions used in this manual to convey
	different types of information.
      </para>
    </sect1>
  </chapter>
  <chapter id="overview">
    <title>Overview</title>
    <para>
      &lzt;'s primary goal is to provide a convienient library of utitlity functions
      to aid in the quick prototyping and development of robust applications.
    </para>
    <sect1 id="Using">
      <title>Using the library</title>
      <para>
	To use the library you will have to add one or more header files to your source 
	and link against the library libzt using your compilers syntax (generally -lzt).
	&lzt; has a number of header files associated with each of the primary sub-libraries.
      </para>
      <para>
	The main header is <filename class=headerfile>zt.h</filename> which should be included
	if you need to access any of the definitions or macros provided by &lzt;.
      </para>
    </sect1>
  </chapter>
